=========================================================
OBJECT SLICING - WHY IS IT A PROBLEM? ⭐⭐⭐⭐⭐
=========================================================

Definition
----------

Object Slicing occurs when a Derived object is copied
into a Base object by value.

Only the Base part is copied.

The Derived-specific members and behavior are lost.

=========================================================
Example (Most Asked Interview Example)
=========================================================

#include <iostream>
using namespace std;

class Animal
{
public:

    virtual void sound()
    {
        cout << "Animal Sound" << endl;
    }
};

class Dog : public Animal
{
public:

    void sound() override
    {
        cout << "Dog Bark" << endl;
    }
};

void makeSound(Animal a)      // Passed by VALUE
{
    a.sound();
}

int main()
{
    Dog d;

    makeSound(d);
}

Output

Animal Sound

=========================================================
Why?
=========================================================

When we call

makeSound(d);

Compiler internally creates

Animal a = d;

This creates a NEW Animal object.

The Dog part is discarded.

Only the Animal portion is copied.

=========================================================
Memory Diagram
=========================================================

Dog Object

+----------------------+
| Animal Part          |
+----------------------+
| Dog Part             |
+----------------------+

          Object Slicing
                 ↓

Animal Object

+----------------------+
| Animal Part          |
+----------------------+

Dog Part is LOST.

=========================================================
Why does Animal::sound() execute?
=========================================================

After slicing,

'a' is no longer a Dog object.

It is a completely new Animal object.

Therefore,

a.sound();

calls

Animal::sound()

instead of

Dog::sound()

=========================================================
Correct Way
=========================================================

Pass by Reference

void makeSound(Animal& a)
{
    a.sound();
}

int main()
{
    Dog d;

    makeSound(d);
}

Output

Dog Bark

=========================================================
Why does this work?
=========================================================

No copy is created.

The reference refers to the original Dog object.

Therefore,

Virtual Function

↓

Runtime Polymorphism

↓

Dog::sound()

=========================================================
Object Slicing vs Reference
=========================================================

Pass by Value

Dog

↓

Animal Copy Created

↓

Dog Part Lost

↓

Animal::sound()

---------------------------------------------------------

Pass by Reference

Dog

↓

No Copy

↓

Original Dog Object

↓

Dog::sound()

=========================================================
When does Object Slicing occur?
=========================================================

✓ Base b = derived;

✓ Function(Base obj)

✓ Returning Base by value

✓ Storing Derived objects in vector<Base>

=========================================================
How to avoid Object Slicing?
=========================================================

Use

✓ Base*

✓ Base&

Instead of

Base object

=========================================================
Most Asked Interview Question
=========================================================

Q. Why is Object Slicing dangerous?

Answer:

Object slicing removes the derived portion of an object
when it is copied into a base object by value. As a
result, derived data members are lost and runtime
polymorphism no longer works because the copied object
is now a pure Base object.***************************VVVVVVIMP

=========================================================
Interview Answer (30 Seconds)
=========================================================

"Object slicing occurs when a derived object is copied
into a base object by value. Only the base-class
subobject is copied, while the derived-specific state
is discarded. This can break runtime polymorphism,
because virtual function calls are now made on the
copied base object instead of the original derived
object. To avoid object slicing, pass or store objects
using base class pointers or references rather than
by value."
